MissionCommands.Message: Good morning {{profileName}}, I am Hector and I will be your instructor today.
Today you will learn how to perform the Apollo Transposition, Docking and Extraction maneuver. Please read DOCKING & TRANSFER chapter in the Apollo Flight Manual for more details.
On the Apollo lunar missions, Transposition, Docking and Extraction maneuver is performed shortly after the trans-lunar injection maneuver.
The Docking system of the Apollo Command Service Module (CSM) is a "probe and drogue" system. The system allows the Apollo Command Service Module to dock with the Apollo Lunar Module.

The Apollo Docking system differences from the Gemini Docking Mechanism in that after docking and locking, the probe and cone mechanism can manually be removed to allow access between the two docked spacecraft.
Once both spacecraft are connected, astronauts can transfer from the Command Service Module (CSM) to the Lunar Module (LM) and backwards.
The Apollo docking system is an important maneuver and as mentioned, mandatory in all Lunar landing missions.
As you may notice, we are already in a stable orbit. Our spacecraft is ready for setting up everything in an appropriate way for this lesson.
Let's get started! Keys are assumed the default configuration. Use the keys you have set in case of changes.
First, ensure that the A/C ROLL jets are powered. Set A1 to MNA.
Set C1 to MNB.
Set A2 to MNA.
Set C2 to MNB.
Next, let us set up the Digital Auto Pilot (DAP) parameters of the PGNCS. Key V48E V21E +11103E V22E +01111E. Press ROGER when done.
This will configure the autopilot to 0.5° deadband, 2.0°/sec max rate and B/D ROLL, 4 jets.

The craft can be commanded using either the backup Stabilization Control System (SCS) or by the Primary Guidance, Navigation, and Control system (PGNCS, pronounced pings). We will use the PGNCS today, but will set up the SCS as well.
Let us prepare the SCS as well. Press "V" on your keyboard, then hit [COMMANDER SEAT] on the [V]IEW SELECTOR panel.
Go to panel [1] [COMMANDER SEAT] and set [MANUAL ATTITUDE] (ROLL) to => [CMD RAT CM] {MIDDLE POSITION}.
Now, set [MANUAL ATTITUDE] (PITCH) to => [CMD RAT CM] {MIDDLE POSITION}.
Finally, set [MANUAL ATTITUDE] (YAW) to => [CMD RAT CM] {MIDDLE POSITION}.
Verify that [ATT DEADBAND MAX] is set to => [MIN] {DOWN POSITION}.
The ATT DEADBAND helps the CSM from rotating at a faster rate-speed than a given speed, it is measured in degrees per second for Roll, Pitch and Yaw axis.
Then, verify that [RATE] is set to => [LOW].
FINALLY set [TRANS CONTR] to => [PWR] {UP POSITION}.
Go to panel [1] [COMMANDER SEAT](Commander's seat) {Lower Panel}. set [ROT CONTR PWR] [NORMAL 1] to => [AC/DC ] {UP POSITION} .
Now, set [ROT CONTR PWR] [NORMAL 2] to => [AC/DC ] {UP POSITION} .
[ROT CONTR PWR] Will allow the Command Service Module (CSM) to use its rotational Reaction Control System (RCS) Thrusters.
Now set [BMAG MODE] (ROLL) to => [ATT 1 2 RATE] {MIDDLE POSITION}.
Next, set [BMAG MODE] (PITCH) to => [ATT 1 2 RATE] {MIDDLE POSITION}.
Finally, set [BMAG MODE] (YAW) to => [ATT 1 2 RATE] {MIDDLE POSITION}.
The Body Mounted Attitude Gyros (BMAG) is capable of detecting the spacecraft's rate. Then, adds the rate to its current know attitude, updating its recorded/learned spacecraft's orientation.
Now, go to panel [1] [COMMANDER SEAT] {Lower Panel}. set [SCS TVC] [PITCH] to => [RATE CMD] {MIDDLE POSITION}.
Next, set [SCS TVC] [YAW] to => [RATE CMD] {MIDDLE POSITION}.
[SCS TVC] Makes the thrust vector to keep inertial fixed during any burn, [RATE CMD] works as some sort of NULL rotation for a while.
Finally, set [CMC MODE] to => [HOLD] {MIDDLE POSITION}.

Now, activate the [COAS]: Press "V" on your keyboard to bring on the [V]IEW SELECTOR panel, then hit [COMMANDERS WINDOW]. Next, press "C" on your keyboard to bring on the [C]OMMUNICATION panel, finally click on [COAS].

Now, we will extend the Docking probe. Press "V" on your keyboard to bring on the [V]IEW SELECTOR panel, then hit [PILOT SEAT]. look near the top side of panel [2]. set [DOCKING PROBE] to => [EXTD/REL] {UP POSITION}.
Next, set [EXTERIOR LIGHTS] to => [RUN/EVA] {UP POSITION}.
Now, set [EXTERIOR LIGHTS] to => [RNDZ] {UP POSITION}.
Next, set [TUNNEL LIGHTS] to => on {UP POSITION}.
Next we will set the EMS to ΔV, this mode will let us measure changes to our velocity (delta-V, ΔV).
Set the EMS to NORMAL to begin detecting detla-V changes.
Ensure you have no angular rates, and that you are in the correct orientation. If the spacecraft is still changing attitude, wait until the maneuver is complete. Press IT'S STABLE to proceed.

Now you are ready to separate the CSM from the Launch Vehicle (SIVB). Press "V" on your keyboard to bring on the [V]IEW SELECTOR panel, then hit [COMMANDER SEAT]. Go to panel [1] {Lower Panel}. press [CSM/LV SEP].

Seperation! Ok, change view so you can see the EMS. Gently [TRANSLATE] in the forward direction [H] until the dV shows +/- 0.5 ft/s. Let it drift away from the SIVB for about 15 seconds. Press ROGER when done.
Let us stop the relative motion between the CSM and SIVB. Gently [TRANSLATE] in the aft direction [N] until the dV shows +/- 0.0 ft/s.

We will now do a full 180° pitch maneuver. You can look at your current attitude and add 180 degrees to it. [PITCH UP] with a rate of about 2°/second until you can see the Lunar Module from its top. Press ROGER when you see it.
Then [ROLL] 45 degrees to the LEFT and align the "T" shaped aim with the COAS. Press ROGER when you have the target of the COAS centered and aligned with the Lunar Module target.

Next [TRANSLATE FORWARD] gently while the "T" shaped aim is aligned with the COAS (keep relative velocity no greater than 0.7 f/s). The T-shape has lights on it, and if the lights from the T shape and the backplate of the target is out of alignment, you need to maneuver. You will see this as you get closer and closer to it.
As you get closer and closer to the target, break towards 0.1 ft/s, and carefully translate and use attitude control to align yourself with the target.
Use as much time as you need to get familiar with the relative motion, and when ready, complete the docking.
Once Docking is successful, Go to panel [2], hit "V" on keyboard [V]IEW [PILOT SEAT], lower area). press [SIVB/LM SEP], and immediately [TRANSLATE] backwards gently.
Ok, the LM is free, [TRANSLATE] backwards gently to pull it out from the launch vehicle.
Congratulations, you just extracted the Lunar Module!

Title: Lesson 10 - Transposition & Docking
Description: The Transposition & Docking maneuver involves separating the Apollo Command/Service Module (CSM) spacecraft from the SIVB launch vehicle, turning it around, and docking its nose to the Apollo Lunar Module (LM). The Lunar Module is then extracted from the adapter.
BriefingText:
BRIEFING

In this lesson, you will learn how to separate the CSM from the Launch Vehicle (LV) SIVB, next you will use the CSM's translation thrusters for translating forward by moving gently the CSM away at a safe distance from the LM and the SIVB (no more than 100 feet), then you will turn around by pitching up the CSM at 180° until facing the Lunar Module (LM). after a little Roll to your left you will align the Lunar module Aim Crosshair with the Apollo CSM COAS, once it is aligned perfectly, you will translate forward until capturing the Lunar Module (LM). finally you will release the Lunar Module from the Launch Vehicle (LV) SIVB, then gently translate backward until separation is successful.
